<a name="109">[109]</a> Juan G. Roederer, "The Physics and Psychophysics of Music - Third edition", Springer-Verlag New York Inc. (1995), p35: "The existence of a finite limit for tone discrimination is an indication that the activated region on the basilar membrane corresponding to a pure tone must have a finite spatial extension. Otherwise, if it were perfectly "sharp," two superposed tones would always be heard as two separate tones as long as their frequencies differed from each other - no matter how small that difference - and no beat sensation would ever arise. Actually, the fact that the roughness sensation persists even beyond the discrimination limit, is an indication that the two activated regions still overlap or interact to a certain degree, at least until the critical band frequency difference is reached."<br>
<a name="110">[110]</a> David M. Howard and James Angus, "Acoustics and Psychoacoustics - Second edition", Focal Press (2001), p75.<br>
