<a name="appendix2"></a>
<h1>Appendix 2: TUNING PREFERENCES THROUGHOUT THE AGES</h1><br>
<b>Header descriptions:</b><br>
IN THEORY    = If applicable, what the person believed was the ideal tuning in theory, and (implied) mostly also for singing, unfretted and other non-fixed pitch instruments.<br>
IN PRACTISE  = What he/she thought was practical and pragmatic for music - including fixed pitch instruments.<br>
UNDETERMINED = One or both of the above two, but we need more information<br><br>


<b>Key abbreviations:</b><br>
JI = just intonation<br>
ET = equal temperament<br>
WT = well temperament<br>
PI = Pythagorean intonation<br>
MT = meantone temperament<br>
M  = microtones<br>
S  = subjective to individual<br>
NC = not concerned<br><br>

<b>Qualifiers:</b>
% = pseudo cross<br>
? = uncertainty<br>
+ = in addition to<br>
! = against<br>
[ ] = reference/citation<br>


<br>
<table border=1 style="font-size:11px">


<tr> <td><b>PERSON’S NAME</b></td> <td><b>YEAR</b></td> <td><b>IN THEORY</b></td> <td><b>IN PRACTISE</b></td> <td><b>UNKNOWN</b></td> <td><b>NOTES</b></td> </tr>
<tr> <td>Donald Tovey</td> <td>?</td> <td>JI [z]</td> <td>-</td> <td>-</td> <td>"enharmonic modulation presupposes just intonation" [z]</td> </tr>
