<a name="appendix3"></a>
<h1>Appendix 3: DEVIATION FROM PURE INTERVALS IN EACH KEY OF JUST INTONATION</h1><br>

The large table further below tests all intervals in each key in a fixed just intonation scale. It demonstrates how it’s not possible to have all intervals equally just for all keys. This is the just intonation scale used:<br>
<br>
<pre>
0 = 1.0		unison
1 = 1.0666	minor second
2 = 1.125	major second
3 = 1.2		minor third
4 = 1.25	major third
5 = 1.333	perfect fourth
6 = 1.40625	diminished fifth
7 = 1.5		perfect fifth
8 = 1.6		minor sixth
9 = 1.666	major sixth
10 = 1.777	minor seventh
11 = 1.875	major seventh
</pre>
<br>
For each key, there will be twelve intervals to test. Each of these will have a deviation from the equal tempered and just intoned equivalent. As a mini-summary for each key, average offsets for all interval deviations (absolute values) are calculated, along with figures for the full chromatic scale, or the diatonic (Ionian) range only.<br>
<br>
<pre>
Key = C (0)
interval: 0  (1.0000)  cents: 0.0000  fromET: 0.0000  fromJI: 0.0000
interval: 1  (1.0666)  cents: 111.73  fromET: 11.731  fromJI: 0.0000
interval: 2  (1.1250)  cents: 203.91  fromET: 3.9100  fromJI: 0.0000
interval: 3  (1.2000)  cents: 315.64  fromET: 15.641  fromJI: 0.0000
interval: 4  (1.2500)  cents: 386.31  fromET: -13.68  fromJI: 0.0000
interval: 5  (1.3333)  cents: 498.04  fromET: -1.955  fromJI: 0.0000
