<b><u>
SUMMARY OF AVERAGE INTERVAL DEVIATION IN CENTS
Key	from ET	(diatonic)  from JI (diatonic)</u></b>
<b>Db</b>	13.523	9.7759      11.731  2.7932
<b>Ab</b>	14.826	8.9378      13.686  3.0723
<b>Eb</b>	16.455	11.451      15.641  6.1446
<b>Bb</b>	8.9611	7.2617      10.427  9.2169
<b>F</b>	8.6353	5.5860      5.2137  3.0723
<b>C</b>	8.6353	6.9826      0       0
<b>G</b>	8.9611	8.9378      5.2137  3.0723
<b>D</b>	9.6128	10.893      10.427  8.9378
<b>A</b>	14.826	12.568      15.641  17.875
<b>E</b>	13.197	12.848      13.686  17.596
<b>B</b>	11.894	12.569      11.731  17.317
<b>F#</b>	10.916	12.290      13.360  17.038	

</pre>

From the results above, it’s clear that the key specially tuned to (C in this case) generally has the smallest cent deviations from both equal temperament and just intonation. The worst keys to use are A major if comparing against just intoned intervals, since many intervals (4,5,6,9,10,11) are off-tune. And according to whether you wish to only use diatonic intervals (Ionian), or the full chromatic range, the worst keys if comparing against equal temperament are E or Eb, respectively.<br>
<br>
